    <div class="alpheios-lex-entry" lemma-id="n8202" body-key="α">
          <b><span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">Ρ.</span></b>  Many words beginning with
            <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ρ</span> originally began with two
          consonants, esp. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ϝρ</span> or <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">σρ</span> (<span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ϝρήγνῡμι,
            σρέω</span>), and the quantitative (metrical) effect of the two
          letters has been preserved in the frequent doubling of <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ρ</span> (<span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἔρρεον</span>).
          What the initial consonant was cannot always be
          determined.</div> <div class="alpheios-lex-footnotes en"> </div>
    <div class="alpheios-lex-alph-source">From <u>
            <u>A Homeric Dictionary</u>
        </u> (Georg Autenrieth, New York, Harper and Brothers, 1891) </div>
